1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:22,250 --> 00:00:25,450
Your apartment was subject to an intervention by the Prague fire department.

3
00:00:25,840 --> 00:00:26,620
I was cooking.

4
00:00:27,700 --> 00:00:30,300
Ozzak was home alone and I forgot to lock the stove.

5
00:00:30,440 --> 00:00:31,860
Sorry, it won't happen again.

6
00:00:32,060 --> 00:00:33,000
I should hope so.

7
00:00:33,850 --> 00:00:37,460
We have more important things to deal with than a pot left on the stove.

8
00:00:37,460 --> 00:00:38,460
It was goulash.

9
00:00:39,350 --> 00:00:42,450
I cleared his airways and put him in the recovery position.

10
00:00:42,950 --> 00:00:46,050
Have you ever considered having him declared legally incompetent?

11
00:00:46,150 --> 00:00:48,290
We think about practically nothing else.

12
00:00:48,750 --> 00:00:49,850
Well, good luck.

13
00:00:50,170 --> 00:00:50,730
Thank you.

14
00:00:54,250 --> 00:00:55,550
Did you see how she was all over me?

15
00:00:55,650 --> 00:00:59,650
When I came to, she was straight up kissing me.

16
00:01:32,750 --> 00:01:33,550
I don't get it.

17
00:01:33,850 --> 00:01:35,260
You're really not happy?

18
00:01:36,150 --> 00:01:37,550
About what exactly?

19
00:01:37,850 --> 00:01:38,880
Jesus, about what?

20
00:01:38,880 --> 00:01:41,240
That I survived when you nearly roasted Ozzak.

21
00:01:41,660 --> 00:01:43,780
Oh, I thought about the fact that you set the kitchen on fire.

22
00:01:43,860 --> 00:01:47,940
Or that the tenants' committee moved you to first place on the list of people who should move out.

23
00:01:48,420 --> 00:01:50,320
What about Roubalova and her six hundred cats?

24
00:01:50,500 --> 00:01:51,420
She had them neutered.

25
00:01:52,750 --> 00:01:55,080
By the way, the building manager suggested that for you too.

26
00:01:55,080 --> 00:01:56,140
But people were against it.

27
00:01:56,950 --> 00:01:57,650
Really?

28
00:01:57,650 --> 00:01:58,990
They wanted to put you down instead.

29
00:02:00,750 --> 00:02:01,850
It's your fault anyway.

30
00:02:01,890 --> 00:02:02,250
What?

31
00:02:02,610 --> 00:02:07,130
If we had more than one pot, I wouldn't have had to make pasta with tuna for two months.

32
00:02:07,510 --> 00:02:10,830
Bro, a real man needs meat, not tuna.

33
00:02:11,030 --> 00:02:12,730
And that's why you set the kitchen on fire?

34
00:02:12,790 --> 00:02:14,290
No, that's why I was making the goulash.

35
00:02:14,750 --> 00:02:18,510
I dozed off for a bit and then woke up when that beautiful firefighter was kissing me.

36
00:02:18,770 --> 00:02:21,490
Uncle, she wasn't kissing you, she was giving you CPR.

37
00:02:22,950 --> 00:02:24,990
Ivuska, trust me, there was nothing artificial about it.

38
00:02:25,150 --> 00:02:28,050
If you'd bought more pots, Ozzak wouldn't have caused any trouble.

39
00:02:29,250 --> 00:02:32,700
Fine, he would've caused different trouble, but at least we'd have something to cook in.

40
00:02:32,700 --> 00:02:34,220
We do have other cookware now, don't we?

41
00:02:34,480 --> 00:02:38,900
The pans have had no Teflon since Ozzak learned there's gold in the Vltava and tried panning.

42
00:02:38,980 --> 00:02:40,120
You shouldn't believe the newspapers.

43
00:02:42,250 --> 00:02:45,750
We used to have pot lids, but they mysteriously vanished during the manly Frisbee tournament.

44
00:02:46,350 --> 00:02:47,850
Couldn't one have been enough?

45
00:02:48,350 --> 00:02:50,150
When they're round, they're hard to catch.

46
00:02:50,150 --> 00:02:50,830
So...

47
00:02:54,850 --> 00:02:57,380
If someone hadn't mixed glue in the remaining pots.

48
00:02:57,380 --> 00:02:59,540
That was necessary, I had to wallpaper.

49
00:02:59,620 --> 00:03:00,500
Why didn't you wallpaper?

50
00:03:00,780 --> 00:03:01,940
Because it hardened.

51
00:03:03,850 --> 00:03:04,950
To make a long story short.

52
00:03:05,040 --> 00:03:07,880
After the pot era comes the era of rolls with pate.

53
00:03:07,880 --> 00:03:12,100
Hold on, Ivuska, rolls give me stomach trouble and pate gives me eczema.

54
00:03:12,550 --> 00:03:13,520
Then make yourself an egg.

55
00:03:14,050 --> 00:03:15,220
In the electric kettle.

56
00:03:15,750 --> 00:03:18,050
Fine, I'll buy the pots.

57
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:20,740
Can you wrap it up for me?

58
00:03:31,350 --> 00:03:34,120
Dad, I was thinking, what are we doing on Saturday?

59
00:03:34,120 --> 00:03:35,120
Got any plans?

60
00:03:35,750 --> 00:03:39,750
Sasha and Lexa want to go to a hip-hop camp, and I thought I'd go with them.

61
00:03:39,950 --> 00:03:41,160
Hip-hop camp?

62
00:03:41,550 --> 00:03:44,450
Is that the TV show where they play basketball?

63
00:03:45,250 --> 00:03:46,850
Come on, dad, keep up with the times.

64
00:03:46,900 --> 00:03:50,140
Hip-hop is a progressive lifestyle that interests young people.

65
00:03:50,140 --> 00:03:55,650
And they get together every summer to discuss what's been happening in this musical genre lately.

66
00:03:56,450 --> 00:03:58,350
Absolutely not.

67
00:03:59,250 --> 00:04:01,450
I'm such an idiot for not saying we're going to play basketball.

68
00:04:02,050 --> 00:04:04,470
You wouldn't do that because you'd be lying to me.

69
00:04:04,850 --> 00:04:06,390
So I'll be stuck at home again.

70
00:04:06,390 --> 00:04:08,310
So you're free on Saturday, right?

71
00:04:08,550 --> 00:04:09,830
No, I'll be doing embroidery.

72
00:04:10,110 --> 00:04:11,190
How about this?

73
00:04:11,550 --> 00:04:12,750
A family trip.

74
00:04:13,850 --> 00:04:15,650
That could be interesting.

75
00:04:16,150 --> 00:04:18,550
If it's like last time, Lexa will be jealous.

76
00:04:18,850 --> 00:04:20,670
I just got mixed up.

77
00:04:20,670 --> 00:04:22,010
Trutnov or Turnov?

78
00:04:22,090 --> 00:04:24,110
Stamp exhibition or erotic fair?

79
00:04:24,450 --> 00:04:25,790
That was great.

80
00:04:26,150 --> 00:04:27,070
And family-friendly?

81
00:04:27,750 --> 00:04:28,510
Family-friendly?

82
00:04:28,510 --> 00:04:28,830
Yeah.

83
00:04:29,580 --> 00:04:31,120
You don't make a baby by licking.

84
00:04:31,660 --> 00:04:32,460
Ozzak.

85
00:04:33,450 --> 00:04:34,850
He's talking about stamps.

86
00:04:36,650 --> 00:04:39,700
The best thing about the trip is that we'll bring home pots.

87
00:04:39,700 --> 00:04:40,860
What is this?

88
00:04:40,860 --> 00:04:49,000
This travel agency is organizing a trip to Kokorin with lunch and a purchase of brand-name cookware.

89
00:04:49,350 --> 00:04:50,360
Looks suspicious.

90
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:52,000
Ozzak, it's free.

91
00:04:52,180 --> 00:04:53,180
Doubly suspicious.

92
00:04:54,250 --> 00:04:56,300
Also music, culture, and lunch.

93
00:04:56,950 --> 00:04:57,650
What lunch?

94
00:04:58,250 --> 00:04:59,650
Beef roulade.

95
00:04:59,750 --> 00:05:00,070
I'm in.

96
00:05:00,450 --> 00:05:01,150
With dumplings?

97
00:05:01,750 --> 00:05:02,310
With rice.

98
00:05:02,310 --> 00:05:02,790
I'm out.

99
00:05:16,050 --> 00:05:18,170
Doesn't that number seem a bit short to you?

100
00:05:18,550 --> 00:05:20,350
No, that's the fire department.

101
00:05:21,550 --> 00:05:22,030
Great.

102
00:05:23,650 --> 00:05:25,220
Hold on, what are you doing?

103
00:05:25,450 --> 00:05:26,800
What's it to you?

104
00:05:26,800 --> 00:05:28,160
You can only call them when there's a fire.

105
00:05:28,340 --> 00:05:30,920
But they must have some private life too, right?

106
00:05:31,380 --> 00:05:33,580
Hello, can I speak with that pretty colleague of yours?

107
00:05:33,880 --> 00:05:35,040
She has a helmet and a little axe.

108
00:05:35,380 --> 00:05:36,400
What, if there's a fire?

109
00:05:36,480 --> 00:05:36,580
No.

110
00:05:37,950 --> 00:05:38,950
Right, it has to be, I see.

111
00:05:39,050 --> 00:05:40,050
Well, thanks.

112
00:05:43,550 --> 00:05:44,450
That didn't work out.

113
00:05:45,150 --> 00:05:45,750
Ozzak?

114
00:05:50,250 --> 00:05:53,250
You want to take this out to the dumpster in the yard?

115
00:05:53,650 --> 00:05:54,780
Is there more somewhere?

116
00:05:55,050 --> 00:05:56,250
In the yard.

117
00:05:57,500 --> 00:05:58,820
That's convenient.

118
00:06:00,750 --> 00:06:04,450
You know, a fire is announced by striking an iron bar against a rail and shouting "fire."

119
00:06:05,750 --> 00:06:09,350
Get yourself a rail and start in about five minutes.

120
00:06:24,250 --> 00:06:25,250
Nice helmet.

121
00:06:28,350 --> 00:06:29,460
Next time then.

122
00:06:30,050 --> 00:06:31,650
That'll be four thousand.

123
00:06:35,050 --> 00:06:39,440
They all say no at first and end up thanking me.

124
00:06:50,450 --> 00:06:51,350
What happened here?

125
00:06:51,950 --> 00:06:53,650
I had a date by the dumpsters.

126
00:06:59,910 --> 00:07:01,730
These pots look suspicious.

127
00:07:01,730 --> 00:07:06,330
Well, they weren't the cheapest, but Milda Ziha said they're the latest thing.

128
00:07:06,550 --> 00:07:09,570
Mr. Ziha said the same thing when he saw there's video on the bus.

129
00:07:10,050 --> 00:07:10,930
Don't be mouthy!

130
00:07:11,350 --> 00:07:14,470
It was a pleasant trip and Milda Ziha was nice company.

131
00:07:14,470 --> 00:07:15,010
He drooled.

132
00:07:15,450 --> 00:07:18,660
Fine, he drooled a little because he had no teeth.

133
00:07:18,850 --> 00:07:20,950
He said someone at home keeps hiding them.

134
00:07:21,420 --> 00:07:22,800
We met on the trip.

135
00:07:22,820 --> 00:07:24,080
He sat next to me on the bus, you know.

136
00:07:25,250 --> 00:07:28,550
He pulled out a disability card, so I had to give him my seat.

137
00:07:28,980 --> 00:07:30,540
Apparently he's a music collector.

138
00:07:30,540 --> 00:07:35,350
The whole way he told me about his modern jazz and how he's always cleaning his trumpets at home.

139
00:07:35,370 --> 00:07:36,750
Probably because they're dirty.

140
00:07:36,750 --> 00:07:41,610
So Ivo, will you make fun of me and Ozzak too when we're old and helpless?

141
00:07:41,950 --> 00:07:43,750
Say something, bro.

142
00:07:43,760 --> 00:07:46,080
I didn't know firefighters also rescue drowned people.

143
00:07:46,880 --> 00:07:48,600
Actually, I'm looking forward to retirement.

144
00:07:48,740 --> 00:07:51,020
You've got savings and plenty of time for everything.

145
00:07:51,260 --> 00:07:54,260
Actually it makes sense, since they're always spraying water around, right?

146
00:07:54,640 --> 00:07:57,840
Milda Ziha has visited every castle and chateau there is.

147
00:07:57,880 --> 00:08:00,000
And next week he's going to Kokos.

148
00:08:02,850 --> 00:08:04,750
His last name really is Ziha after all.

149
00:08:06,950 --> 00:08:08,150
Is there a river nearby?

150
00:08:21,280 --> 00:08:22,720
Everyone there was doing this.

151
00:08:23,170 --> 00:08:24,710
Significantly better than Milda Ziha.

152
00:08:24,970 --> 00:08:26,570
They all got drunk and fell asleep.

153
00:08:26,730 --> 00:08:28,050
I couldn't not be among them, right?

154
00:08:28,050 --> 00:08:29,330
They all buy the same things.

155
00:08:29,490 --> 00:08:30,810
Well, so do retirees.

156
00:08:31,030 --> 00:08:32,770
A vest, a cap, and a cane.

157
00:08:32,950 --> 00:08:34,630
A woman, her uniform, nothing.

158
00:08:38,350 --> 00:08:40,190
Is there going to be some reggae festival?

159
00:08:40,550 --> 00:08:43,450
There's a reggae session in Liberec on Saturday.

160
00:08:43,550 --> 00:08:46,250
He'll go wrapped in a carpet.

161
00:08:46,450 --> 00:08:49,550
Sasha wants to go, you want to go, and I want to go.

162
00:08:53,450 --> 00:08:56,650
I want to go, but dad will ban it the moment I explain what a reggae session is.

163
00:08:56,770 --> 00:08:58,170
He didn't even know what hip-hop camp was.

164
00:08:58,430 --> 00:08:59,210
I don't want to go.

165
00:09:00,270 --> 00:09:00,930
Wait, Sasha!

166
00:09:01,330 --> 00:09:02,250
What are you doing?

167
00:09:02,270 --> 00:09:03,050
It's going to be awesome!

168
00:09:03,750 --> 00:09:06,270
They'll just sing about stealing cars and doing drugs again.

169
00:09:06,270 --> 00:09:07,090
I don't like that.

170
00:09:07,250 --> 00:09:08,030
These guys are different.

171
00:09:08,550 --> 00:09:10,150
They only sing about nice things.

172
00:09:10,250 --> 00:09:12,410
They sway around and always smile.

173
00:09:12,410 --> 00:09:12,850
Really?

174
00:09:13,450 --> 00:09:14,250
Then I'd go.

175
00:09:14,470 --> 00:09:14,910
Well.

176
00:09:15,850 --> 00:09:17,750
And I'll go with dad to Kokorin.

177
00:09:18,010 --> 00:09:19,170
Just make something up for him.

178
00:09:19,490 --> 00:09:20,650
Lexa, you shouldn't lie.

179
00:09:20,950 --> 00:09:22,720
Not everyone faints when they lie.

180
00:09:23,050 --> 00:09:25,850
Right, like when you tried to tell auntie it looks good on her.

181
00:09:29,050 --> 00:09:32,380
Try telling him we're going to the world plowing championship.

182
00:09:33,150 --> 00:09:35,150
He won't buy that, he's not that senile.

183
00:09:38,010 --> 00:09:38,610
Jealous, huh?

184
00:09:40,650 --> 00:09:41,910
Nice vest.

185
00:09:41,910 --> 00:09:42,910
It has many pockets.

186
00:09:42,910 --> 00:09:46,230
It's practical, look, you can fit a lot in it.

187
00:09:46,230 --> 00:09:46,570
Yeah.

188
00:09:50,230 --> 00:09:50,710
Insulin?

189
00:09:51,590 --> 00:09:53,150
And it's still possible to rob Milda.

190
00:09:53,330 --> 00:09:54,470
He survived without teeth too.

191
00:09:55,230 --> 00:09:56,690
It's amazingly warm.

192
00:09:56,830 --> 00:09:58,410
Milda lent it to me to warm up.

193
00:09:58,470 --> 00:10:00,670
I waited for him two hours at the zoo.

194
00:10:00,790 --> 00:10:02,290
He was two hours late?

195
00:10:02,470 --> 00:10:03,510
No, he didn't come at all.

196
00:10:04,050 --> 00:10:05,150
He was waiting at the botanical garden.

197
00:10:07,060 --> 00:10:07,920
Hey, dad?

198
00:10:08,120 --> 00:10:08,300
Yeah?

199
00:10:09,450 --> 00:10:12,410
Could I go somewhere with the twins this weekend?

200
00:10:12,410 --> 00:10:12,910
Where?

201
00:10:14,150 --> 00:10:15,450
To a reggae session.

202
00:10:16,950 --> 00:10:20,450
I hope it's not another music event involving drug consumption.

203
00:10:20,540 --> 00:10:21,040
No.

204
00:10:22,020 --> 00:10:23,300
So what is it then?

205
00:10:24,600 --> 00:10:25,200
Regen...

206
00:10:25,200 --> 00:10:25,800
Regen...

207
00:10:25,800 --> 00:10:27,440
Regeneration.

208
00:10:28,750 --> 00:10:29,750
Like massages.

209
00:10:30,550 --> 00:10:35,440
Everyone holds an incense stick and enjoys life.

210
00:10:35,650 --> 00:10:37,650
You learn to calm down there.

211
00:10:37,850 --> 00:10:39,050
Regeneration?

212
00:10:39,850 --> 00:10:42,550
Yeah, like a course.

213
00:10:43,350 --> 00:10:45,220
Like a course in regeneration techniques?

214
00:10:45,220 --> 00:10:45,920
Yeah, yeah.

215
00:10:47,480 --> 00:10:48,020
Yeah.

216
00:10:54,650 --> 00:10:55,550
Why did you let her go?

217
00:10:56,050 --> 00:10:58,250
She's exhausted.

218
00:10:58,450 --> 00:11:00,050
She needs regeneration.

219
00:11:00,110 --> 00:11:00,650
Desperately.

220
00:11:02,450 --> 00:11:17,350
It's not her fault, it's those famous pots of yours.

221
00:11:17,790 --> 00:11:20,030
You put them on the stove and they start smoking.

222
00:11:20,250 --> 00:11:22,310
You must have done something wrong.

223
00:11:22,850 --> 00:11:25,970
I poured in water and turned on the stove, describe the mistake.

224
00:11:26,450 --> 00:11:27,890
That's a mystery.

225
00:11:28,150 --> 00:11:30,850
I'll have to ask Milda what experience he's had with them.

226
00:11:30,870 --> 00:11:31,930
Oh, he called.

227
00:11:31,930 --> 00:11:34,730
God, I forgot we're playing afternoon chess.

228
00:11:35,150 --> 00:11:36,150
He probably did too.

229
00:11:36,450 --> 00:11:38,410
He said you're going to feed the swans.

230
00:11:38,410 --> 00:11:39,610
Why doesn't he call my cell?

231
00:11:40,060 --> 00:11:41,980
I told him that too, but he didn't know what it is.

232
00:11:45,450 --> 00:11:48,150
Damn, so there was a fire here and I'm waiting by the pond.

233
00:11:52,850 --> 00:11:57,250
Ozzak, are you really sure this is the best remedy for cockroaches?

234
00:11:58,290 --> 00:11:58,770
Absolutely.

235
00:11:59,070 --> 00:12:00,470
And do we even have any?

236
00:12:01,150 --> 00:12:04,050
It's good to be prepared.

237
00:12:05,260 --> 00:12:05,740
Good.

238
00:12:08,350 --> 00:12:10,450
Was it you who reported a kitten in a tree?

239
00:12:10,750 --> 00:12:11,670
What's it to you?

240
00:12:11,950 --> 00:12:13,250
There isn't one up there.

241
00:12:14,170 --> 00:12:15,570
It chewed through the rope, the little pest.

242
00:12:15,570 --> 00:12:18,750
But don't think I don't know what you're up to.

243
00:12:19,050 --> 00:12:21,770
Seven small fires, one fake drowning.

244
00:12:22,050 --> 00:12:24,030
You're trying to turn Majka's head, aren't you?

245
00:12:24,030 --> 00:12:24,630
Majka?

246
00:12:25,250 --> 00:12:26,730
Majka is mine.

247
00:12:27,050 --> 00:12:31,350
Strike one more match and I'll strangle you with a hose, got it?

248
00:12:32,650 --> 00:12:33,250
Cheers.

249
00:12:39,350 --> 00:12:40,150
Caveman.

250
00:12:43,050 --> 00:12:43,750
Majka.

251
00:12:45,440 --> 00:12:50,240
Hello, this is Tomas.

252
00:12:50,890 --> 00:12:52,010
Well, six letters.

253
00:12:53,150 --> 00:12:55,550
Listen, I'm doing a crossword and I'm stuck.

254
00:12:55,650 --> 00:13:01,150
Jamaican music style, six letters, starts with R. Are you doing one too?

255
00:13:04,210 --> 00:13:05,210
You don't know either.

256
00:13:05,210 --> 00:13:07,450
Well, bye then, bye.

257
00:13:09,150 --> 00:13:12,350
Damn, they can't even make crosswords properly anymore.

258
00:13:13,690 --> 00:13:14,670
Hi, kids.

259
00:13:15,370 --> 00:13:16,830
How was it?

260
00:13:17,210 --> 00:13:17,470
Great.

261
00:13:18,050 --> 00:13:19,950
Why are you so incredibly muddy?

262
00:13:20,160 --> 00:13:23,600
On the second day there were mud baths for volunteers.

263
00:13:23,900 --> 00:13:26,040
The media says mud is good for joints.

264
00:13:26,180 --> 00:13:26,900
And for the skin.

265
00:13:27,330 --> 00:13:29,190
Sasha, why are your eyes so red?

266
00:13:29,310 --> 00:13:30,910
It's from the smoke, Mr. Pacovsky.

267
00:13:31,010 --> 00:13:32,490
From aromatherapy, you know?

268
00:13:32,850 --> 00:13:34,450
Aroma, aroma, therapy.

269
00:13:34,650 --> 00:13:38,450
Wait, why does Lexa have those braids?

270
00:13:39,020 --> 00:13:39,880
Because he's an idiot.

271
00:13:41,470 --> 00:13:41,950
Right.

272
00:13:42,950 --> 00:13:45,150
Mr. Pacovsky, I wanted to tell you, I love you.

273
00:13:47,860 --> 00:13:48,340
Wait.

274
00:13:49,050 --> 00:13:50,700
And how did you spend it?

275
00:13:50,700 --> 00:13:51,180
Well.

276
00:13:51,610 --> 00:13:54,330
We finally went with Milda to return the pots.

277
00:13:54,410 --> 00:13:55,790
And did they give you money back?

278
00:13:56,250 --> 00:13:57,530
Something better, kids.

279
00:13:58,150 --> 00:14:00,710
We got a voucher for two for a pedicure.

280
00:14:00,950 --> 00:14:03,050
We'll go together with Tonik Zehak.

281
00:14:03,070 --> 00:14:04,110
You mean Zehak?

282
00:14:04,230 --> 00:14:05,510
No, no, that's really his name.

283
00:14:05,610 --> 00:14:07,650
Tonik Zehak, wonderful person.

284
00:14:08,650 --> 00:14:10,450
OK, great, but what are we going to cook in?

285
00:14:11,050 --> 00:14:12,250
Tonik says meals on wheels delivers his food.

286
00:14:14,590 --> 00:14:17,010
It's pleasant, tasty, and easy to digest.

287
00:14:17,850 --> 00:14:20,450
So overcooked carrots and cream of wheat.

288
00:14:24,750 --> 00:14:25,950
Lexa, Mr. Ozzak, you wanted something?

289
00:14:28,150 --> 00:14:29,850
I need you to call for help.

290
00:14:30,260 --> 00:14:30,940
Should I get something?

291
00:14:30,940 --> 00:14:33,650
Not right now, but I expect to get stuck in a sewer on Saturday night.

292
00:14:36,050 --> 00:14:38,950
Yeah, sewers are pretty dangerous, I get stuck there all the time.

293
00:14:39,350 --> 00:14:41,450
But unlike you, I never know in advance.

294
00:14:42,450 --> 00:14:43,450
I have a date down there.

295
00:14:44,850 --> 00:14:47,550
I can't, Mr. Ozzak, the girls and I are going to CzechTek.

296
00:14:47,750 --> 00:14:48,550
Want to come with us?

297
00:14:48,850 --> 00:14:49,550
What is it?

298
00:14:49,850 --> 00:14:51,850
A little event, it'll be intense.

299
00:14:52,050 --> 00:14:54,450
Any chance of running into firefighters there?

300
00:14:54,650 --> 00:14:55,650
More like cops.

301
00:14:55,680 --> 00:14:56,140
Then no thanks.

302
00:14:56,840 --> 00:14:57,660
I'll go to the sewer.

303
00:15:03,510 --> 00:15:04,190
What's that?

304
00:15:04,530 --> 00:15:04,950
Flippers.

305
00:15:06,870 --> 00:15:07,590
And this?

306
00:15:08,700 --> 00:15:09,120
Smoke bombs.

307
00:15:10,850 --> 00:15:12,350
So it's near Trutnov.

308
00:15:12,350 --> 00:15:14,450
Smoke bombs, smoke bombs, wait.

309
00:15:14,850 --> 00:15:15,510
What are they for?

310
00:15:15,850 --> 00:15:16,510
For cops.

311
00:15:16,510 --> 00:15:17,310
For firefighters too?

312
00:15:18,050 --> 00:15:18,730
Yeah, them too.

313
00:15:18,950 --> 00:15:19,590
Got more?

314
00:15:19,590 --> 00:15:21,070
Yeah, mom has a ton.

315
00:15:21,270 --> 00:15:23,610
Whenever they lock themselves in the pub after football, she throws one in.

316
00:15:26,650 --> 00:15:28,450
Maybe I won't go to the sewer after all.

317
00:15:30,030 --> 00:15:31,770
Ivo, what if your dad won't let you?

318
00:15:32,030 --> 00:15:33,510
Reggae went through, everything will.

319
00:15:36,850 --> 00:15:37,850
So it's near Turnov.

320
00:15:37,850 --> 00:15:39,350
I already bought train tickets.

321
00:15:39,450 --> 00:15:41,210
Great, it's not that far.

322
00:15:41,250 --> 00:15:43,150
But will I really like it there?

323
00:15:43,270 --> 00:15:44,550
It'll be like a funfair.

324
00:15:44,930 --> 00:15:45,370
Really?

325
00:15:45,850 --> 00:15:48,050
Just without swings, carousels, or cotton candy.

326
00:15:49,650 --> 00:15:50,950
But will there be dogs?

327
00:15:51,550 --> 00:15:54,650
And if the cops show up again this year, there'll be even more dogs.

328
00:15:54,650 --> 00:15:56,030
OK then, I love dogs.

329
00:15:57,750 --> 00:15:58,250
Great, now we just need to figure out what to tell dad.

330
00:16:00,220 --> 00:16:02,100
But it has to be something totally safe.

331
00:16:02,550 --> 00:16:03,750
I have a great idea.

332
00:16:04,450 --> 00:16:05,850
How about a regeneration festival?

333
00:16:06,540 --> 00:16:06,980
Lexa.

334
00:16:07,750 --> 00:16:08,850
We already went to one.

335
00:16:09,370 --> 00:16:09,890
When?

336
00:16:11,650 --> 00:16:12,690
Sasha, say something.

337
00:16:13,050 --> 00:16:14,190
Where would you most like to go?

338
00:16:14,190 --> 00:16:15,950
A cross-stitch embroidery course.

339
00:16:16,030 --> 00:16:18,490
I always wanted to go but mom always said no.

340
00:16:19,210 --> 00:16:20,230
Perfect!

341
00:16:20,950 --> 00:16:23,250
It's so dumb he'll definitely buy it.

342
00:16:24,490 --> 00:16:25,270
Sorry, Sasha.

343
00:16:32,690 --> 00:16:34,730
So, everyone knows what to do, right?

344
00:16:34,830 --> 00:16:35,630
I'm not supposed to faint.

345
00:16:38,340 --> 00:16:38,860
Hi!

346
00:16:39,580 --> 00:16:41,260
So how's it going?

347
00:16:42,240 --> 00:16:42,760
Champs!

348
00:16:43,450 --> 00:16:45,950
Good, why are you yelling at us?

349
00:16:45,950 --> 00:16:46,430
Me?

350
00:16:47,550 --> 00:16:52,450
Sorry, I was feeding swans with Milda and Milda forgot his hearing aid.

351
00:16:52,460 --> 00:16:52,940
Right.

352
00:16:52,940 --> 00:16:57,000
Hey, dad, I'd like to go to this event this weekend with the twins.

353
00:16:57,000 --> 00:16:57,920
To Turnov for CzechTek.

354
00:16:58,460 --> 00:16:59,720
Wait, what's CzechTek?

355
00:17:00,550 --> 00:17:02,150
That sounds somehow familiar.

356
00:17:02,350 --> 00:17:03,150
CzechStech.

357
00:17:03,960 --> 00:17:05,380
International embroidery course.

358
00:17:06,960 --> 00:17:07,440
Embroidery?

359
00:17:08,050 --> 00:17:10,100
Since when are you three interested in embroidery?

360
00:17:10,100 --> 00:17:10,320
Yeah.

361
00:17:10,480 --> 00:17:11,200
Me too.

362
00:17:11,320 --> 00:17:11,800
Me too.

363
00:17:13,650 --> 00:17:14,750
Why are you panting like that, Sasha?

364
00:17:15,460 --> 00:17:15,940
I...

365
00:17:16,590 --> 00:17:17,470
She's exhausted.

366
00:17:17,950 --> 00:17:20,910
She embroidered a tablecloth with cross-stitch all night.

367
00:17:21,150 --> 00:17:26,050
And also chain stitch and pearl stitch, that one's best for petals.

368
00:17:27,850 --> 00:17:30,350
We embroider with Sasha a lot.

369
00:17:31,150 --> 00:17:32,250
Sasha?

370
00:17:33,250 --> 00:17:34,350
Really?

371
00:17:35,950 --> 00:17:39,850
Sasha, Sasha, dad is asking if you like embroidery.

372
00:17:40,760 --> 00:17:43,400
I love embroidery, I look forward to these courses all summer.

373
00:17:43,800 --> 00:17:45,820
So you three are going to embroider?

374
00:17:46,250 --> 00:17:47,350
Is that right, Sasha?

375
00:17:48,240 --> 00:17:48,760
Huh?

376
00:17:51,950 --> 00:17:55,180
I love embroidery, I look forward to these courses all summer.

377
00:17:55,650 --> 00:17:57,250
I don't know, I don't know, I don't know.

378
00:17:57,550 --> 00:17:58,920
You can't trust young people.

379
00:17:59,150 --> 00:18:03,080
Tonik said his son promised him a spa and shoved him in a nursing home instead.

380
00:18:03,080 --> 00:18:04,680
But we have an invitation.

381
00:18:04,880 --> 00:18:05,360
Show me.

382
00:18:07,650 --> 00:18:09,250
There's a phone number here.

383
00:18:14,750 --> 00:18:17,950
That six, damn, why do they make these buttons so small?

384
00:18:25,350 --> 00:18:28,250
Good afternoon, I have your invitation here.

385
00:18:30,050 --> 00:18:33,490
You say embroiderers from around the world?

386
00:18:33,850 --> 00:18:35,950
And is it safe there?

387
00:18:36,950 --> 00:18:38,410
Only thimbles, I see.

388
00:18:40,150 --> 00:18:42,050
And where will they be staying?

389
00:18:43,650 --> 00:18:46,650
Boys in barracks and girls in a convent?

390
00:18:47,050 --> 00:18:48,050
Excellent.

391
00:18:48,550 --> 00:18:50,350
Thank you, God be with you.

392
00:18:53,750 --> 00:18:57,250
Well then I apologize for not believing you.

393
00:18:59,950 --> 00:19:01,050
Mom called me.

394
00:19:02,150 --> 00:19:03,050
She didn't want anything.

395
00:19:12,580 --> 00:19:15,560
Why are you being all clever now?

396
00:19:15,920 --> 00:19:18,020
I wish I had your money.

397
00:19:18,840 --> 00:19:21,580
Don't pretend you can't hear me.

398
00:19:24,250 --> 00:19:32,650
Well, embroidery.

399
00:19:32,830 --> 00:19:33,750
We'll see Ivuska now.

400
00:19:33,750 --> 00:19:46,850
Since morning, thousands of young techno fans have been arriving to, as usual, take drugs, ignore hydration, listen to deafening music, and fight with the police.

401
00:19:50,150 --> 00:19:52,330
Milda says you can't trust young people.

402
00:19:52,330 --> 00:19:56,850
Tomas, there's still a chance they're at that embroidery course.

403
00:19:56,950 --> 00:19:59,950
But why did Lexa bring that smoke bomb?

404
00:20:00,450 --> 00:20:01,400
Christ's foot.

405
00:20:01,550 --> 00:20:03,050
Tomas, what kind of language is that?

406
00:20:03,250 --> 00:20:04,160
That's what Milda says.

407
00:20:04,550 --> 00:20:06,150
He also says "dang nabbit."

408
00:20:06,180 --> 00:20:07,760
It really lets off steam too.

409
00:20:07,880 --> 00:20:09,620
You should take a look at yourselves.

410
00:20:09,880 --> 00:20:10,980
You're talking like a senior citizen.

411
00:20:11,420 --> 00:20:13,260
Iva just went to a music festival.

412
00:20:13,560 --> 00:20:14,940
You call that music?

413
00:20:15,360 --> 00:20:18,680
Well, even CzechTek wasn't what he expected, so he knows more about it.

414
00:20:19,150 --> 00:20:20,650
He lost his hearing back then.

415
00:20:20,750 --> 00:20:25,120
And when the techno kids found out who called the cops on them, his teeth too.

416
00:20:26,250 --> 00:20:27,650
Come on, bro, we have to get them out of there.

417
00:20:28,120 --> 00:20:30,500
Go alone, I need the apartment to myself today anyway.

418
00:20:31,160 --> 00:20:32,700
Good thing I still have friends.

419
00:20:33,280 --> 00:20:34,720
Milda is rallying the guys.

420
00:20:34,720 --> 00:20:37,850
If there's four of us, we'll get a group discount on the bus.

421
00:20:37,950 --> 00:20:39,460
Don't worry about us.

422
00:20:39,750 --> 00:20:41,000
The boys fought at Dukla.

423
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:42,000
Exactly.

424
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:43,620
Don't underestimate us.

425
00:20:43,850 --> 00:20:47,520
Tonik, the guys from their encounter with skinheads couldn't even stand up.

426
00:20:47,520 --> 00:20:48,120
Really?

427
00:20:48,240 --> 00:20:48,360
Yeah.

428
00:20:48,950 --> 00:20:50,340
He ran into them at the hospital.

429
00:20:50,750 --> 00:20:54,150
They even had the nerve to claim they were looking for the oncology ward.

430
00:21:51,550 --> 00:21:52,350
Hello, I'd like to report a fire.

431
00:21:53,450 --> 00:21:55,550
Horakova eleven, as always.

432
00:21:55,950 --> 00:21:58,750
And hurry, my brother could be back any minute.

433
00:21:58,870 --> 00:21:59,310
Yeah.

434
00:22:23,250 --> 00:22:24,250
What did I tell you?

435
00:22:24,260 --> 00:22:25,180
It's him again.

436
00:22:25,340 --> 00:22:26,440
I suppose it's my fault, huh?

437
00:22:26,660 --> 00:22:28,280
You must have provoked him somehow.

438
00:22:28,650 --> 00:22:29,980
During the CPR.

439
00:22:29,980 --> 00:22:30,500
How so?

440
00:22:31,140 --> 00:22:32,120
Did you stick your tongue in there?

441
00:22:32,320 --> 00:22:33,820
I must be dreaming.

442
00:22:33,960 --> 00:22:35,320
You know what, then resuscitate yourself.

443
00:22:35,500 --> 00:22:38,540
Wait, you know how much I hate resuscitating guys.

444
00:22:38,760 --> 00:22:40,420
But you don't mind with women, right?

445
00:22:40,520 --> 00:22:41,880
Like that blonde last week.

446
00:22:42,650 --> 00:22:43,050
I thought she was fibrillating.

447
00:22:44,620 --> 00:22:44,920
Yeah.

448
00:22:45,750 --> 00:22:47,550
You were giving her a heart massage while she was on the phone telling her husband everything's fine.

449
00:22:50,550 --> 00:22:51,650
When this one fibrillates.

450
00:22:51,850 --> 00:22:53,450
Come on, he's faking it.

451
00:22:54,350 --> 00:22:55,250
I'm not sure.

452
00:22:55,650 --> 00:22:56,990
By the river he had no pulse at all.

453
00:22:57,150 --> 00:22:59,550
Well that was obviously just so you'd notice him.

454
00:22:59,650 --> 00:23:00,750
At least he's doing something.

455
00:23:00,750 --> 00:23:01,090
What about you?

456
00:23:01,650 --> 00:23:03,850
When's the last time you did something for me?

457
00:23:03,870 --> 00:23:05,330
Wait, what do you mean?

458
00:23:05,550 --> 00:23:06,450
I don't know, something.

459
00:23:07,650 --> 00:23:09,650
When's the last time you took me to the river, for example?

460
00:23:10,550 --> 00:23:11,950
Two weeks ago when we were filling cisterns.

461
00:23:14,870 --> 00:23:17,890
Sometimes I wonder if you even still love me.

462
00:23:18,390 --> 00:23:20,310
How can you even say that?

463
00:23:20,830 --> 00:23:23,530
This poor guy has poisoned himself with mushrooms three times because of me.

464
00:23:23,690 --> 00:23:26,170
Once he crawled into a sewer pipe and almost drowned.

465
00:23:26,270 --> 00:23:26,830
What about you?

466
00:23:27,450 --> 00:23:31,090
Am I supposed to start acting like some psychopath too, or what?

467
00:23:31,090 --> 00:23:31,630
I don't know.

468
00:23:32,450 --> 00:23:34,190
You just used to try harder.

469
00:23:34,250 --> 00:23:35,730
Before, before, before.

470
00:23:36,050 --> 00:23:38,730
You used to pole dance for me at the fire station too.

471
00:23:38,730 --> 00:23:39,970
Is that what you want?

472
00:23:42,650 --> 00:23:45,650
Could we fit that in today? Those bruises are still fresh.

473
00:23:46,050 --> 00:23:46,850
What about him?

474
00:23:47,750 --> 00:23:50,550
If you want, I'll resuscitate him for you, no problem.

475
00:23:52,480 --> 00:23:53,680
No, no, no.

476
00:23:55,050 --> 00:23:56,590
He was really faking it.

477
00:23:57,050 --> 00:23:57,690
What, daddy?

478
00:23:57,690 --> 00:23:58,430
But hurry.

479
00:23:59,150 --> 00:24:00,350
I'll turn on the siren.

480
00:24:00,950 --> 00:24:07,860
I told you not to go after those hooligans.

481
00:24:07,940 --> 00:24:09,320
But they're not to blame.

482
00:24:09,440 --> 00:24:12,120
The police stopped us right when we arrived.

483
00:24:12,180 --> 00:24:12,640
What?

484
00:24:12,760 --> 00:24:14,120
That's disgusting.

485
00:24:14,400 --> 00:24:16,380
I heard they beat up kids, but...

486
00:24:16,720 --> 00:24:17,800
Even seniors?

487
00:24:17,800 --> 00:24:22,120
We wanted to show ID and the cops figured out how old I am.

488
00:24:22,120 --> 00:24:22,520
So what?

489
00:24:23,750 --> 00:24:33,040
The guys jumped on me, called me a stool pigeon and hooligan, Milda swung a cane at me and the peacekeeper forgot who I am and started yelling that I'm a techno snitch.

490
00:24:33,250 --> 00:24:35,250
The police took them away then.

491
00:24:36,750 --> 00:24:37,650
Did you find Iva?

492
00:24:38,750 --> 00:24:41,250
I'm just happy I survived.

493
00:24:47,950 --> 00:24:49,290
Dad, what happened to you?

494
00:24:49,450 --> 00:24:52,250
Well well, domestic arts enthusiasts.

495
00:24:53,050 --> 00:24:54,970
So how was your sewing course?

496
00:24:55,350 --> 00:24:56,650
In Trutnov!

497
00:24:57,080 --> 00:24:58,540
We were in Turnov.

498
00:24:58,960 --> 00:25:01,260
You can ask Lexa, he bought the tickets.

499
00:25:01,600 --> 00:25:04,880
And how did you like the sewing course?

500
00:25:05,650 --> 00:25:07,780
I've had better weekends.

501
00:25:07,850 --> 00:25:09,320
I'm not asking you, Lexa.

502
00:25:09,850 --> 00:25:12,850
I'll ask the last person I can still trust here, Sasha.

503
00:25:16,970 --> 00:25:18,870
It was wonderful, Mr. Pacovsky.

504
00:25:18,990 --> 00:25:21,570
I learned the double pulled butter stitch and I was good at it.

505
00:25:21,730 --> 00:25:23,530
And I embroidered this for Mr. Ozzak.

506
00:25:26,750 --> 00:25:27,950
Well you deserved it, huh?

507
00:25:28,750 --> 00:25:31,350
And what did you embroider, Ivuska, huh?

508
00:25:35,550 --> 00:25:38,950
I was supposed to embroider Trutnov, not Turnov, but I only managed this.

509
00:25:41,050 --> 00:25:42,940
Bro, dang nabbit, I really am senile.

510
00:25:43,350 --> 00:25:45,720
So Ivuska, sorry for not believing you.

511
00:25:45,850 --> 00:25:48,750
Just next time someone else is buying the tickets.

512
00:25:52,350 --> 00:25:55,540
Bro, if you're planning another date, arrange it by the dumpsters.

513
00:25:55,540 --> 00:25:57,640
No, Roubalova is sending us goulash.

514
00:25:58,350 --> 00:26:02,450
Because she found out who called the firefighters to save her kitten.

515
00:26:04,050 --> 00:26:07,990
And she also said we can keep the pot because I explained that we're in need.

516
00:26:08,350 --> 00:26:09,850
You know, we have a pot again.

517
00:26:10,150 --> 00:26:10,650
Great, so tomorrow it's pasta with tuna.
